2. $P(v \to r_v) = p_v$
3. We add edge $(u, v)$ with weight $w$.

Path $r_u \to u \xrightarrow{w} v \to r_v$.
$P(r_u \to r_v) = P(r_u \to u) + w + P(v \to r_v) \pmod 2$.
$P(r_u \to u) = P(u \to r_u) = p_u$ (since we are working modulo 2, the direction doesn't change the parity, assuming we use the defined paths). Wait, this is tricky. If $p_u$ is the parity $u \to r_u$, then $r_u \to u$ has parity $p_u$.

Let's recheck the path calculation when merging $r_u$ to $r_v$:
We want $P(r_u \to r_v)$.
Path: $r_u \to u \xrightarrow{w} v \to r_v$.
$P(r_u \to u) = p_u$.
$P(v \to r_v) = p_v$.
So, $P(r_u \to r_v) = p_u + w + p_v \pmod 2$.

Set $\text{parent}[r_u] = r_v$.
Set $parity[r_u] = p_u + w + p_v \pmod 2$.

