The nodes $u$ and $v$ are already in the same component. Adding edge $(u, v)$ with weight $w$ creates a cycle.
The path from $u$ to $v$ via the existing component structure has parity $p_u + p_v \pmod 2$ (Path $u \to r_u \to v$, where $r_u = r_v$).
The new cycle created by $(u, v)$ has parity: $(p_u + p_v) + w \pmod 2$.
For the graph property to hold, this cycle parity must be 0.
Condition for accepting the edge: $(p_u + p_v + w) \pmod 2 = 0$.
If this condition holds, the edge is added (and we increment the count). If it fails, we reject it.

If $r_u \neq r_v$:
The nodes are in different components. We merge them, say setting $r_u$'s parent to $r_v$.
We need to determine the new parity for $r_u$ relative to $r_v$.
We want $P(r_u \to r_v) \pmod 2$.
We know:
1. $P(u \to r_u) = p_u$
2. $P(v \to r_v) = p_v$
3. We add edge $(u, v)$ with weight $w$.

Path $r_u \to u \xrightarrow{w} v \to r_v$.
$P(r_u \to r_v) = P(r_u \to u) + w + P(v \to r_v) \pmod 2$.
$P(r_u \to u) = P(u \to r_u) = p_u$ (since we are working modulo 2, the direction doesn't change the parity, assuming we use the defined paths). Wait, this is tricky. If $p_u$ is the parity $u \to r_u$, then $r_u \to u$ has parity $p_u$.

Let's recheck the path calculation when merging $r_u$ to $r_v$:
We want $P(r_u \to r_v)$.
Path: $r_u \to u \xrightarrow{w} v \to r_v$.
$P(r_u \to u) = p_u$.
$P(v \to r_v) = p_v$.
So, $P(r_u \to r_v) = p_u + w + p_v \pmod 2$.

Set $\text{parent}[r_u] = r_v$.
Set $parity[r_u] = p_u + w + p_v \pmod 2$.

The edge is always added in this case, as connecting two previously disconnected components cannot create a cycle.

